		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30015599">Oh Code Geass, how I absolutely love you.<br />
<br />
Here we have a show that takes the tried and tested formula of Sunrise mecha, blends in some Real Robot and Super Robot tropes and gives us a series that through mixing a wide variety of genres (in true Full Metal Panic fashion) manages to be an extremely appealing show regardless of genre preference. The show is rather interesting in its approach to various themes and extensively developing certain characters, no doubt the most crucial of them being Lelouch. Hell, I'd argue that not liking Lelouch is the equivalent of not liking the show itself.<br />
The various themes the show covers are varied and all fleshed out to some extent, ranging from imperialism to nationalism's hypocrisy to what it meant for Lelouch to fight as Zero. The series is however very flawed and the plot and certain events have to be taken with a grain of salt, as  Ipf kindly presented for us above. I nevertheless believe that, as a piece of pure entertainment as well as a thought provoking series in terms of themes, Code Geass goes beyond its initial purpose and delivers one of the most powerful messages to come out of anime (that lying to achieve a greater purpose is not an evil thing to do) and easily one of greatest finales in anime history. <br />
It has plot holes, it gets a bit too ahead of itself with its plot twists and I can certainly see why many people dislike it, if not outright hate it. But Code Geass nevertheless is a series that catches the attention of the viewers and is among the most emotionally gripping series I've ever seen, and very few anime in general and mecha in particular stand out from the crowd as much as this one.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://i.imgur.com/8NuZt.png" /></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
