		  <td colspan="2" class="forum_category"><a name="post8"></a><a name="msg30080513"></a><div style="margin: 5px 0px;">
		<div style="float: right; padding-right: 3px; color: #ffffff;">#<a href="#msg30080513" class="postnum">8</a></div>
		<div style="padding-left: 3px;">04-16-14, 8:52 PM</div>
		</div></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser30080513" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/BigSimo"><strong>BigSimo</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/BigSimo"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/102929.jpg" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: Oct 2008<br>
		  Posts: 5116
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30080513"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>sushiisawesome said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>Oh Code Geass, how I absolutely love you.<br />
<br />
Here we have a show that takes the tried and tested formula of Sunrise mecha, blends in some Real Robot and Super Robot tropes and gives us a series that through mixing a wide variety of genres (in true Full Metal Panic fashion) manages to be an extremely appealing show regardless of genre preference. The show is rather interesting in its approach to various themes and extensively developing certain characters, no doubt the most crucial of them being Lelouch. Hell, I'd argue that not liking Lelouch is the equivalent of not liking the show itself.<br />
The various themes the show covers are varied and all fleshed out to some extent, ranging from imperialism to nationalism's hypocrisy to what it meant for Lelouch to fight as Zero. The series is however very flawed and the plot and certain events have to be taken with a grain of salt, as  Ipf kindly presented for us above. I nevertheless believe that, as a piece of pure entertainment as well as a thought provoking series in terms of themes, Code Geass goes beyond its initial purpose and delivers one of the most powerful messages to come out of anime (that lying to achieve a greater purpose is not an evil thing to do) and easily one of greatest finales in anime history. <br />
It has plot holes, it gets a bit too ahead of itself with its plot twists and I can certainly see why many people dislike it, if not outright hate it. But Code Geass nevertheless is a series that catches the attention of the viewers and is among the most emotionally gripping series I've ever seen, and very few anime in general and mecha in particular stand out from the crowd as much as this one.<!--quote--></div><br />
I couldn't have put it better.<br />
<br />
I am of the firm belief that Taniguchi Goro, the man behind Geass, knew <em>exactly</em> what he was doing the entire time. I'm not going to argue against people who think the show is bad, because yes it is frequently illogical and full of coincidences. BUT, I don't like to call the twists and turns 'asspulls'. I think the show is purposely ridiculous in this respect, and that the goal from the beginning was to continually up the ante, with every twist outdoing the one preceding it in terms of sheer idiocy. <br />
I don't have any proof that this was the case, but I think Goro is a very talented director, and based on the other two shows of his I've seen (Planetes + Infinite Ryvius), I feel he has a very strong sense of direction and progression. Planetes in particular is a show founded on logic and (half of the time) realism. It is one of the best in this regard. Code Geass is the complete opposite. It wouldn't make sense for the man who directed Planetes to direct a completely illogical show and not realize just how illogical it all was. I just don't see it.<br />
<br />
Besides Goro, there were two other dudes who played a role in Geass' story composition. Those two went on to make Guilty Crown, a show that attempted to use the model of Code Geass and implement the same twists and turns, yet which failed miserably. Why? Because those two didn't understand what Goro was doing. They thought all you needed was a mass of cliches and asspulls. They were wrong.<br />
Ok, so I'm heavily assuming things here, but it makes sense to me to think of it like this. I feel such a strong emotional connection to Code Geass. I have watched it THREE TIMES all the way through, and my third viewing was by far the most enjoyable of the three. I thought that by then all the 'flaws' would expose themselves, that its stupidity would get on my nerves. This didn't happen.<br />
I've always wondered what it is that allows someone to watch Code Geass while suspending their disbelief. I know a lot of Code Geass fans are the same people that love shit like Naruto and Attack on Titan, and it makes me feel like a fool. But there are quite a few people who are in the same boat as me - usually I struggle with anything illogical in visual media. I like to think I'm good at separating the positives from the negatives; I have a strong grasp on when an anime is truly great in all aspects - my interest in the technical side of things, the way each area of a show's production influences it and to what degree, has continued to rise over the years.<br />
Still, Code Geass is something that baffles me in this regard. I really can't pin down what makes me love it. But I will try.<br />
<br />
Firstly, high production values. The animation quality is high, and very consistent. CLAMP's art is bonkers but very distinct, and characters/locations are instantly memorable. Fight scenes are well animated. I can't note anything that hinders it in this regard.<br />
Geass has a very strong soundtrack. It is diverse, but focused, and perfectly complements the bursts of fabulousness with celebratory trumpets and upbeat drums and spanish guitars (yep). On the other end of the spectrum are the tracks by Hitomi; beautiful melancholic minimal songs. The soundtrack has so many memorable themes; quite an achievement when far too many shows lean heavily on one theme in particular. The dynamic soundtrack works wonders, driven primarily by trumpets and a female choir. Roughly 50 different songs per season. Yeah.<br />
Additionally: an ensemble cast of voice actors. All bring extraordinary colour to their characters (EXTRA colour in addition to the distinctive 'each character gets a unique hair colour' thing). All memorable performances. Charles played by Wakamoto. The incredibly versatile Sakurai Takahiro as the eternally troubled Suzaku. Inoue Norihiro perfectly restrained as Schneizel. Minami Omi brings a perfect naive defiance to Euphemia.<br />
But the standout is of course Fukuyama Jun as Lelouch. Never has a voice been so weirdly deep. But he parallels this with his normal voice as Lelouch being Lelouch, rather than Zero. He gets so into character, you can feel the desperation growing throughout R2, especially when he screams out Nunally's name. He perfectly encapsulates all sides of Lelouch. Just amazing.<br />
<br />
And that brings me to what I kind of figure to be the show's strongest aspect: Lelouch. He holds everything together. One of the most compelling characters I have seen. Yes, he is overpowered, but the real draw of Lelouch is his emotions. He is flawed. Nunally is his flaw, and it's when she becomes an important part of the plot that Lelouch's true colours show, and it is delicious. He is a wounded man, SO deeply wounded in so many ways. It is ridiculous, but ridiculously entertaining to watch him balance his emotions with his intelligence. <br />
His relationship with Suzaku is so frustrating (because Suzaku is so frustrating AND frustrated), but again, very compelling. Constantly Lelouch's main hindrance, but Lelouch's best friend. Oh god is it a perfect coincidence, but it is so very entertaining. And then, the moment when Lelouch emerges as emperor with Suzaku as his loyal knight. Holy shit, the most perfectly ridiculously satisfying thing ever.<br />
<br />
The entire cast of characters is very strong. It is one of the largest casts ever, yet each character is distinct. Most are shallow, yes, but somehow...all are distinct. They all feel like characters. I think it's because every character has a motivation. Every character besides the main bunch IS basically a motivation. The all have something driving them into action in some way, and when they all intersect it is a bloodbath of emotion. Constantly. The main themes are loyalty and betrayal, and the characters perfectly encapsulate this. <br />
<br />
The ending is again ridiculous but the entire show's emotional peak. It is perfect.<br />
<br />
I think I kind of stopped explaining myself properly there, and I've glossed over a lot....but I find it hard to talk about this show in objective terms, because Code Geass is for me an emotion-based experience. I think people who say it is bad are glossing over a lot of things though. There is a lot of creative talent behind this show (most of which stems from Taniguchi Goro...I believe), and in terms of presentation, there are few shows that can match this.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
