		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30166531"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>twinbells said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><!--link--><a href="http://www9.georgetown.edu/faculty/irvinem/theory/sontag-notesoncamp-1964.html" rel="nofollow">For those who need help understanding the appeal of Code Geass and Valvrave.</a><br />
<br />
Plot holes and absurdity in Code Geass are a given. To point them out is to miss the point entirely.<!--quote--></div>If you agree with the thought that Code Geass is unintentionally camp (the best kind of camp, according to the article), then I don't think there is a "point" to miss. There are failings, which one can enjoy or dislike. <br />
<br />
The currently airing adaptation of Jojo has many camp scenes, here's one of them off the top of my head- Jonathan Joestar says "Have you ever looked at the bottom of your neck? All Joestars have a star birthmark on it!!" to which his daughter and grandson respond with utter and hilarious bewilderment. The shock scene lies on the completely unlikely premise that the characters really never looked at their naked back in a mirror, which is hilarious- and the plot never stops taking the statement seriously which gives the campy feeling, while keeping full control over the work. On the other hand, Code Geass has moments like the one when you wonder what trick the writers will use to save all the Japanese, and you get the whole cosplay thing, an answer that's a mix of cringeworthy and funny, that the story itself -doesn't- take seriously seriously (the Britannian officials don't buy into the silly trick) but it makes it work by having Suzaku convince Britannia to let them go. As far as camp goes, I find Jojo's a lot better than Code Geass' which I mainly see as terrible writing.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
