		<tr>
		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser30224473" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/BigSimo"><strong>BigSimo</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/BigSimo"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/102929.jpg" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: Oct 2008<br>
		  Posts: 5116
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30224473"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>lpf said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>@BigSimo: I've seen the former queen of MAL say that she loved Code Geass as a brilliant comedy. I can totally see where you and she are coming from. I know I am biased myself, since part of the reason why I can't accept Code Geass for the over-the-top nonsense that it could be (like TTGL, great comparison Litrydow gave) is because of all the fans that take it seriously as you said. From what I've heard of Valvrave, danz makes a good point as well. I've also read a post that claimed that the only people who can enjoy chuuni stories are those who actually take them seriously (like the general Code Geass fandom) and those who can sit back and enjoy the potentially unintentional over-the-top dialogue without being embarrassed.<br />
<br />
Also a note about the voice acting. Wakamoto sounded like he was parodying himself (as he often does these days). Fukuyama was in tune with the plot, totally chuuni. I found it funny at times.<!--quote--></div><br />
uh oh i think i've dug myself a hole. I didn't mean that I take it as a great comedy. I take it seriously, and get completely caught up in the drama and find myself emotionally attached. Admittedly when there is a really ridiculous plot twist I can't help but laugh at the absurdity of it, but ultimately yes, I take it seriously.<br />
I guess in this sense I'm not too different from the masses who love it. <br />
The point I was trying to make (I think) was that the approach of 'let's pack it with ridiculous plot twists and forego logic in favour of just about everything else' actually works in its favour. What I understand a lot of the arguments against Geass to be are that its creators didn't realize that what they were creating was riddled with holes and leaps in logic - I think they (particularly Taniguchi) intended on this approach. That despite the absurdity of Geass' events, there was always a strong focus on where things were headed. I remember reading some dude's post somewhere about Geass and he basically countered a lot of arguments against the show that detailed plot holes. He rebuked a bunch of the plot holes. The guy had watched the show like 7 times. After completing Geass for the third time, I wasn't at a loss. Everything was a lot clearer the third time round, and whereas with previous viewings I had felt like there were definitely things that didn't add up, the third time round a lot of those things made sense. I wish I could pinpoint examples, but I'd need to watch it all again to refresh my memory...so I guess I have no credibility.<br />
<br />
Look, I don't know where I'm going with this. Basically I'm trying to justify why I enjoy it so much, why it affects me so.... because I don't think it's bad. I think it's well-made. Its pacing is relentless, intoxicating. I just can't imagine not getting caught up in it, the same way people who don't like it probably can't imagine getting caught up in it. It's a weird one. <br />
<br />
People compare it Valvrave. I think Valvrave is terrible. I think Code Geass is great. I think the difference is characters. Code Geass has Lelouch, a fantastic anti-hero, as well as the rest of the cast who are mostly shallow but very distinct; Valvrave has instantly unlikable leads and forgettable side characters (i only watched two eps of Valvrave admittedly). I think there is definitely something about Code Geass that makes it good. It is not a bad show, and one day I will blow you all away with why this is so.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
