		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30301327">I think the first two short comments on the show reflect greatly what Code Geass is. It's an entry-level anime that gives it's audience all the explosive tropes with little bars held. Episode one's shock value doesn't fade as the series progresses - it's a level maintained throughout the series. People have become embarrassed to like Code Geass. While it's easy to get caught up in the bombastic dialogue and narrative turns, Code Geass is incredible. Code Geass is a production that could only exist in the medium of anime because it draws heavily on so many anime influences and structures.<br />
<br />
It's Legend of the Galactic Heroes for teenagers and while it's existence may be unnecessary, it has done great things for the medium of anime and has created a gateway into the currently stunted medium letting people who don't like anime know "anime is okay." No matter how you cut it up, Code Geass has made an enormous impact on anime and therefore should be celebrated.<br />
<br />
Obviously Code Geass is with it's flaws - most glaringly it's ridiculous twists... but they're a double-edged sword. Without them the anime would fade into obscurity like Valvrave. Code Geass is a show that constantly writes itself into a corner to beg the viewer, "you think we can't get out of this?" The plot is not about will Lelouch win, it's how. Critic's think themselves incredible when pointing out plot holes in action series. Code Geass wasn't meant to be believable or realistic. Code Geass is self-aware, and truly a show of it's own breed. It's a charming and unique anime.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/animelist/Detective&amp;sclick=1"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/signature/Detective.png" /></a> </div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
